This error means you're calling `.map()` on a variable that is `undefined` at the time it runs. Let me trace the root cause.

**Most likely scenario:** You're fetching data from an API, and the component renders BEFORE the data arrives. During that first render, your data variable is `undefined`, and you try to call `.map()` on it.

**The fix depends on where the data comes from:**

**If it's from useState:**
```javascript
// BAD — initial state is undefined
const [items, setItems] = useState();

// GOOD — initial state is empty array
const [items, setItems] = useState([]);
```

**If it's from an API response:**
```javascript
// BAD — data.items might not exist yet
return data.items.map(item => <div key={item.id}>{item.name}</div>)

// GOOD — optional chaining + fallback
return (data?.items ?? []).map(item => <div key={item.id}>{item.name}</div>)
```

**If it's from props:**
```javascript
// BAD — parent might not pass items
function List({ items }) {
  return items.map(...)
}

// GOOD — default parameter
function List({ items = [] }) {
  return items.map(...)
}
```

Share your component code and I'll identify the exact line and fix it. Use view_file if it's already in our project.

For fintech, you want fonts that communicate trust, precision, and professionalism while still feeling modern.

**My recommendation:**

**Display/headings:** DM Sans (600-700 weight) — geometric, clean, modern but not cold. Works at all sizes. Alternative: Plus Jakarta Sans if you want slightly warmer.

**Body text:** DM Sans (400-500 weight) — same family keeps it cohesive. For mixed-family: pair with Source Sans 3 (excellent legibility at small sizes, important for data-dense dashboards).

**Data/numbers:** JetBrains Mono or Fira Code — monospace for tabular data so digits align vertically. Critical for financial tables.

**Specific CSS:**
```css
--font-display: 'DM Sans', sans-serif;
--font-body: 'DM Sans', sans-serif;
--font-mono: 'JetBrains Mono', monospace;

h1, h2, h3 { font-family: var(--font-display); font-weight: 700; letter-spacing: -0.02em; }
body { font-family: var(--font-body); font-weight: 400; font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.5; }
.amount, .metric, td.number { font-family: var(--font-mono); font-variant-numeric: tabular-nums; }
```

**Load:** `https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=DM+Sans:wght@400;500;600;700&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;500&display=swap`

**Avoid for fintech:** Playfair Display (too editorial), Bebas Neue (too bold/casual), any handwritten fonts. Fintech users spend hours staring at this — readability at 14px is everything.

Here's a polished todo app with smooth add/remove animations and a clean dark interface.

```tsx:App.tsx
import { useState, useRef, useEffect } from 'react'

interface Todo {
  id: string
  text: string
  completed: boolean
  entering: boolean
  exiting: boolean
}

export default function App() {
  const [todos, setTodos] = useState<Todo[]>([])
  const [input, setInput] = useState('')
  const inputRef = useRef<HTMLInputElement>(null)

  const addTodo = () => {
    const text = input.trim()
    if (!text) return
    const newTodo: Todo = { id: crypto.randomUUID(), text, completed: false, entering: true, exiting: false }
    setTodos(prev => [newTodo, ...prev])
    setInput('')
    inputRef.current?.focus()
    setTimeout(() => {
      setTodos(prev => prev.map(t => t.id === newTodo.id ? { ...t, entering: false } : t))
    }, 50)
  }

  const toggleTodo = (id: string) => {
    setTodos(prev => prev.map(t => t.id === id ? { ...t, completed: !t.completed } : t))
  }

  const removeTodo = (id: string) => {
    setTodos(prev => prev.map(t => t.id === id ? { ...t, exiting: true } : t))
    setTimeout(() => {
      setTodos(prev => prev.filter(t => t.id !== id))
    }, 300)
  }

  const remaining = todos.filter(t => !t.completed).length

  return (
    <div style={{ minHeight: '100vh', background: '#0f0f14', color: '#f0f0f5', fontFamily: "'DM Sans', sans-serif", display: 'flex', justifyContent: 'center', padding: '80px 24px' }}>
      <div style={{ width: '100%', maxWidth: 520 }}>
        <h1 style={{ fontSize: '2rem', fontWeight: 700, marginBottom: 8, letterSpacing: '-0.02em' }}>Tasks</h1>
        <p style={{ color: '#7a7a8e', marginBottom: 32, fontSize: '0.95rem' }}>{remaining} remaining</p>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', gap: 12, marginBottom: 32 }}>
          <input
            ref={inputRef}
            value={input}
            onChange={e => setInput(e.target.value)}
            onKeyDown={e => e.key === 'Enter' && addTodo()}
            placeholder="What needs to be done?"
            style={{ flex: 1, padding: '14px 18px', background: 'rgba(255,255,255,0.05)', border: '1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.08)', borderRadius: 12, color: '#f0f0f5', fontSize: '0.95rem', outline: 'none', fontFamily: 'inherit', transition: 'border-color 0.2s ease' }}
          />
          <button onClick={addTodo} style={{ padding: '14px 24px', background: '#6366f1', border: 'none', borderRadius: 12, color: '#fff', fontWeight: 600, cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '0.95rem', fontFamily: 'inherit', transition: 'background 0.2s ease' }}>
            Add
          </button>
        </div>
        <div style={{ display: 'flex', flexDirection: 'column', gap: 8 }}>
          {todos.length === 0 && (
            <p style={{ textAlign: 'center', color: '#7a7a8e', padding: '48px 0', fontSize: '0.9rem' }}>No tasks yet. Add one above.</p>
          )}
          {todos.map(todo => (
            <div
              key={todo.id}
              style={{
                display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: 14, padding: '16px 18px',
                background: 'rgba(255,255,255,0.04)', border: '1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.06)',
                borderRadius: 12, transition: 'all 0.3s ease',
                opacity: todo.exiting ? 0 : todo.entering ? 0 : 1,
                transform: todo.exiting ? 'translateX(20px)' : todo.entering ? 'translateY(-10px)' : 'none',
              }}
            >
              <div
                onClick={() => toggleTodo(todo.id)}
                style={{
                  width: 22, height: 22, borderRadius: 6, border: todo.completed ? 'none' : '2px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.2)',
                  background: todo.completed ? '#6366f1' : 'transparent', cursor: 'pointer',
                  display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', justifyContent: 'center', flexShrink: 0,
                  transition: 'all 0.2s ease'
                }}
              >
                {todo.completed && <span style={{ color: '#fff', fontSize: 12 }}>✓</span>}
              </div>
              <span style={{ flex: 1, textDecoration: todo.completed ? 'line-through' : 'none', color: todo.completed ? '#7a7a8e' : '#f0f0f5', transition: 'color 0.2s ease' }}>
                {todo.text}
              </span>
              <button
                onClick={() => removeTodo(todo.id)}
                style={{ background: 'none', border: 'none', color: '#7a7a8e', cursor: 'pointer', fontSize: '1.1rem', padding: 4, lineHeight: 1, transition: 'color 0.2s ease' }}
              >
                ×
              </button>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  )
}
```

Features: DM Sans font, dark theme with indigo accent, animated add (fade in from top) and remove (slide out right), checkbox with smooth fill, empty state message, remaining count, Enter key to add, auto-focus input after adding. No external dependencies beyond React.

That's expected behavior, not a bug. Mobile devices don't have hover — there's no mouse cursor to hover with. Touch devices fire hover states inconsistently (some trigger on first tap, some don't at all).

**The fix:**

Wrap hover styles in a media query that only applies on devices with a real pointer:

```css
/* Only apply hover on devices that support it */
@media (hover: hover) {
  .card:hover {
    transform: translateY(-4px);
    box-shadow: 0 12px 24px rgba(0,0,0,0.12);
  }
}

/* For mobile, use active (tap) state instead */
.card:active {
  transform: scale(0.98);
  transition: transform 0.1s ease;
}
```

The `@media (hover: hover)` query returns true only on devices with a real hover capability (mouse, trackpad). Touch-only devices skip it entirely.

For the active/tap feedback, keep the transition short (0.1s) so it feels snappy and responsive to touch.

